<text>Inserting an image

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

To insert an image, choose &quot;Insert&gt;Picture&gt;From File&quot; (keyboard action: ALT+SHIFT+I), or press the Insert Picture Button &quot; &quot;, there will be a file dialog with which you can select an image from your file system and import it into the word processor.

There are only three image formats supported: PNG, GIF and JPEG. You cannot import images in other formats such as BMP. If you do have a picture in other formats, use a graphics tool to convert its format to GIF or JPEG or PNG first.

An image on the page can be removed in the same way a character is removed (i.e. using the DELETE or BACKSPACE key), or use the &quot;Cut&quot; menu available from the pop-up menu when the image is right-clicked (or CTRL+click on Mac OS X without a multiple-button mouse). The pop-up menu also provides some other options and access to the information of the image:

  
[This is a screenshot of the pop-up menu over an image.]

At this time, there are some limitations with images embedded in text in our word processor: 

   An image lies in line with the text. No other text wrapping styles are supported.
   An image cannot be resized and rotated while in the page.
   An image cannot be edited and processed.

You can also insert a snapshot image from the Snapshot Gallery. The menu path for this action is: &quot;Insert &gt; Picture &gt; From Snapshot Gallery&quot;. Once you choose this menu item, the Snapshot Gallery will appear, if there are images stored in it. You can then choose an image and press the &quot;Insert&quot; button of the Snapshot Gallery. The selected snapshot image will be inserted to the page at the location where the caret is.

 
NOTE: There is a bug related to the alignment of an image with a component in the same line. There is a workaround for this bug.

